    {
      "id": "commentary",
      "html": "<h2>commentary</h2>  <p>The text was found in situ alongside a second such base (<a href=\"http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic003124\" target=\"_blank\">ISic003124</a>) for Nymphodoros son of Eukleides; and it is an almost certain hypothesis that the other two statue bases (IG XIV.434 and 435 = <a href=\"http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic001259\" target=\"_blank\">ISic001259</a> and <a href=\"http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic001260\" target=\"_blank\">ISic001260</a>) were originally part of the same set of honorific monuments, all in the immediate vicinity of what is assumed to be the Hellenistic bouleuterion, on the northern side of the original agora (and subsequently subsumed under later Roman structures). While the bases can all confidently be dated to the period between c.200 and 50 BCE, the exact chronology, as noted above, is open to some dispute. For a very full and detailed discussion of the context, concentrated on the two bases known since the 18th century, see Muscolino 2009-2010.</p>  <p>It is worth comparing the variety in the formulation of these four bases. The base for Nymphodoros son of Philistion is the only example at Tauromenion to employ the full formula dedicating the honorand in the accusative to the divine in the dative (in this case 'all the gods', which is encountered with some frequency in Hellenistic Sicily, especially along the north coast of the island). The base for Nymphodoros son of Eukleides employs the same accusative formulation, but without the dative dedication to a divinity, or the reflexive phrase τᾶς εἰς αὑτὸν, in similar fashion to the base for Olympis son of Olympis (which substitutes his Pythian victory as the reason, rather than his goodwill to the city). The base for Marcellus simply presents the name of the Roman governor in the nominative.</p>  "
    },
    {
      "id": "bibliography",
      "html": "<h2>bibliography</h2>  <ul><li> 32.0936 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000796\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000796</a>  </li><li> Bacci 1980-1981 739-741 fig. 2a base 2 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002176\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002176</a>  </li><li> Muscolino 2009-2010 436-437 fig. 23 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001732\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001732</a>  </li></ul>  <ul><li></li></ul>  "
    },
    {
      "id": "handnote",
      "html": " <p>Deeply incised letters with a regular module (although with a little bit of cramping in lines 2 and 3) and of even height throughout. Terminal serifs of a simple wedge form. Alpha is consistently pronounced broken bar; epsilon has shorter middle bar, only lightly connected, with slight overlap of the top and bottom bar; theta is a full circle, with a short detached mid-stroke; kappa has shorter arms (especially the lower arm); mu has vertical outer strokes, with the middle strokes extending three-quarters of the way down to the base line; omicron is full size; pi has slightly overlapping crossbar, with equal length verticals; rho a large rounded eye; sigma has parallel top and bottom strokes, with a slight extension at the join of the mid-strokes; phi has small eye with slightly extended vertical; omega is slightly smaller than the other letters, tear-drop shaped, joined to the base line (but the eye does not close before the baseline) </p> <p> Types list: <a href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Α-type2.html\" target=\"_blank\">Α type2</a> <a href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Ε-type2.html\" target=\"_blank\">Ε type2</a> <a href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Ε-type2.3.html\" target=\"_blank\">Ε type2.3</a> <a href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Ε-type2.3.1.html\" target=\"_blank\">Ε type2.3.1</a> <a href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Ε-type2.3.2.html\" target=\"_blank\">Ε type2.3.2</a> <a href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Θ-type1.html\" target=\"_blank\">Θ type1</a> <a href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Θ-type1.2.html\" target=\"_blank\">Θ type1.2</a> <a href=\"https://kingsdigitallab.github.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Κ-type1